    en: "New York Criminal Procedure Law Article 710 lets a defendant move to suppress evidence that was obtained through an unlawful search or seizure, an involuntary statement, or an improper identification procedure. Suppression is the remedy for Fourth Amendment violations (unreasonable search), Fifth Amendment violations (coerced confession or failure to warn of Miranda rights), Sixth Amendment violations (denial of counsel during questioning), and statutory violations. A granted suppression motion typically means the challenged evidence cannot be used at trial, often forcing the prosecution to reduce charges or dismiss. The motion is usually filed before trial and resolved at a pretrial hearing (Mapp, Huntley, Dunaway, Wade, or similar hearings)."
